The Root Entry Point
When a user taps an app icon on their iPhone, iOS looks for the @main attribute to know strictly where the app officially starts executing.
Here is the Swift Entry Point (App.swift):
import SwiftUI

@main
struct MyApp: App {
    var body: some Scene {
        WindowGroup {
            ContentView() // ⬅️ Points to the first Screen
        }
    }
}






NoteReact Equivalent (index.js)





import React from 'react';
import ReactDOM from 'react-dom/client';
import App from './App';

const root = ReactDOM.createRoot(document.getElementById('root'));
root.render(
  &lt;React.StrictMode&gt;
    &lt;App /&gt; {/* ⬅️ Points to the first Screen */}
  &lt;/React.StrictMode&gt;
);




What About main.swift?
Before @main was introduced in Swift 5.3 (2020), the conventional entry point was a special file named main.swift. It is the only file in a Swift project that is allowed to contain top-level executable code — meaning code written directly at the file’s root scope, outside of any struct, class, or func.
// main.swift (legacy entry point)
import UIKit

UIApplicationMain(
    CommandLine.argc,
    CommandLine.unsafeArgv,
    nil,
    NSStringFromClass(AppDelegate.self)
)
The name main.swift is not arbitrary — the Swift compiler treats it as a reserved filename with special rules:

Only one main.swift can exist per target. Having more than one will cause a compile error.
Top-level expressions are only legal here. Any other .swift file that tries to run code at the top level (outside a type or function) will fail to compile.
@main replaced it. Modern SwiftUI apps use @main on a struct instead, which is cleaner and avoids manually calling UIApplicationMain. You will still encounter main.swift in older UIKit projects or Swift command-line tools.







NoteNode.js Parallel





main.swift behaves much like a Node.js entry file (e.g. index.js run directly via node index.js) — it is the one file where code runs immediately at the top level without needing to be wrapped in a function or class. All other files must export or be explicitly called.

How Screens Work (Views)
In Swift, there is no generic &lt;div&gt;. A screen is always built strictly as a Struct conforming to the View protocol.
Here is what ContentView.swift looks like.
import SwiftUI

struct ContentView: View {
    // ⬇️ Q3: Where is the data? 
    // Data is held explicitly inside the struct instance using Property Wrappers like @State.
    @State private var userName: String = "Charlotte" 

    // ⬇️ Q2: When does render happen? 
    // ANY time the property marked as @State explicitly changes, the 'body' automatically re-renders.
    var body: some View {
        VStack {
            Text("Hello, \(userName)")

            Button("Change Name") {
                // ⬇️ Q1: Is this single-threaded?
                // Yes. By default, ALL UI code executes strictly on the Main Thread.
                userName = "Swift Developer"
            }
        }
    }
}

Q1. Is this single-threaded?

UI rendering in Swift is purely single-threaded.
All interface rendering runs on what Apple calls the Main Thread.
In the code block above, when you tap the button, that line of code immediately executes on the Main Thread to guarantee a buttery-smooth 60 to 120 frames per second response.
Rule: If you fetch data from the internet (which is slow), you must explicitly push that task to a “Background Thread” to avoid freezing the screen.



Q2. When does the render happen?
Rendering is reactive, triggered purely by a change in State.

When the button is tapped and userName changes from “Charlotte” to “Swift Developer”, SwiftUI detects the change in @State and immediately invalidates the current body.
SwiftUI then re-computes the physical screen to match the updated state. This is highly optimized and functionally matching how React triggers a re-render when you call setState().



Q3. Where is the data stored?
Fact: Local state data is stored specifically inside the Struct instance using Property Wrappers.

Structs are highly efficient, temporary data structures.
The data (userName) only exists for as long as this specific screen is visually alive on the device.
If you have global data (state you want to share across multiple screens), you store it in classes called ObservableObjects, which act very much like React Context or an overarching Redux Store.

Actors (Concurrency-Safe Reference Types)
Actors are a modern Swift feature built exclusively to prevent Data Races (when two parts of your app try to change the same memory at the exact same millisecond).






TipJS / React Perspective



JavaScript is single-threaded; the Event Loop handles tasks one by one, so parallel memory collisions rarely happen. Swift is genuinely multi-threaded. Code runs in parallel. Actors are required to safely manage shared data across these parallel threads.


Key Traits:

Behavior: Reference type (Shared memory).
Safety: Automatically isolates its state. It forces outside code to wait in a queue (await) to interact with it.
Usage: High-performance, concurrent background tasks.

actor SafeCounter {
    var count = 0

    func increment() {
        count += 1
    }
}

let counter = SafeCounter()

// Because the actor is heavily guarded, you must pause and "await" your turn to access it:
// await counter.increment()

Swift functions use the func keyword, enforce strict types on both the arguments and the output, and explicitly mandate how you call them.
Key differences compared to JavaScript:

Arguments require explicit types (e.g., name: String).
A function’s return type is declared with a right-facing arrow -&gt;.
When invoking a function, you must explicitly write out the parameter’s name to make the code highly legible.

func name(parameterName: parameterType) -&gt; ReturnType {
    // Code to execute
    return value
}

name() becomes a global function existing in the global namespace of your specific module
you can call name() in any file within the same module

private func name(parameterName: parameterType) -&gt; ReturnType { ... }

You cannot call this from another file. It is restricted exclusively to the file (or enclosing scope) it was declared in.

public func name(parameterName: parameterType) -&gt; ReturnType { ... }

You can call this from any other file, including files in entirely different modules (like if you are building a Framework that another app imports).

// 1. Standard Swift Function
func greet(name: String) -&gt; String {
    return "Hello \(name)" // Notice string interpolation uses \( ) not ${ }
}

let message = greet(name: "Charlotte") // ⬅️ MUST explicitly write 'name:' 


// 2. SwiftUI View (Struct returning UI)
struct Greet: View {
    let name: String

    var body: some View {
        Text("Hello \(name)")
    }
}

// ⬇️ Called exactly like a function using named parameters!
Greet(name: "Charlotte")






NoteWhat does this look like in JavaScript & React?





// 1. Standard JavaScript Function
function greet(name) {
    return "Hello " + name;
}

greet("Charlotte"); // Called without explicitly naming the parameters


// 2. React Functional Component (Returns UI)
export default function Greet({ name }) {
    return &lt;h1&gt;Hello {name}&lt;/h1&gt;;
}

// Called using JSX, where props act similarly to named parameters
&lt;Greet name="Charlotte" /&gt;



Function Parameter Omitting: If you want Swift to behave exactly like JavaScript and let you omit the parameter name when calling a function, you explicitly place an underscore _ before the parameter name in the definition.
func fastGreet(_ name: String) -&gt; String {
    return "Hey \(name)"
}

// Now it looks exactly like JavaScript when invoked:
let fastMessage = fastGreet("Charlotte")

All executable code must live inside body of a function
a function declared at the top level of a file is a global function

